<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,494,1287]" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,494,518]" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Variability.</emphasis>
Two female forms could be distinguished in the available specimens. Form A (
<figureCitation box="[159,259,526,551]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Figs. 5–8</figureCitation>
) sensu K. G. Blair (see New records) is represented by typically coloured females with a completely orange body except of the black metepimeron and two black spots on each elytron, one isolated in the middle and one small at the apex. Female form B (
<figureCitation box="[992,1093,591,615]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
) is light red with black middle and hind legs and a black mesepisternum, metepimeron, mesepimeron, metepisternum and metaventrite. The elytra are orange with a black basal band, isolated central spot and black apical spot. The length of metatarsomeres is also different: form A has the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[206,222,717,732]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">nd</superScript>
metatarsomere short and robust (but not flattened from above as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[966,1117,720,743]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipunctata">
<emphasis box="[966,1117,720,743]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M. bipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and shorter than the 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[383,396,749,764]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">rd</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[411,515,751,775]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Figs. 6–7</figureCitation>
). Form B has the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[718,734,749,764]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">nd</superScript>
metatarsomere long and slender and almost as long as the 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[396,409,781,796]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">rd</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[424,529,783,807]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Figs. 2–3</figureCitation>
). Moreover, the species is quite variable in the shape of the elevated process at the apex of pronotum: in form A it is quite distinct and long (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1112,815,839]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), while in form B it is reduced with a small cavity (
<figureCitation box="[677,742,847,871]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1554,1573]" captionTargetBox="[243,1036,219,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[243,1036,219,1530]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–8. Macrosiagon elegans (Marseul, 1876). 1–4 – female form ‘B’ from Yemen; 5–8 – female form ‘A’ from ‘Arabia’. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325206/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Both forms are 
<quantity box="[927,1027,847,871]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" unit="mm" value="8.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="6.0">6–10 mm</quantity>
long and overlap in their range of distribution. I assume that the morphological and colour differences between both forms are related to their development (possibly different hosts?) and have no taxonomic value. Form C (
<figureCitation box="[436,499,943,967]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1461,1480]" captionTargetBox="[115,1089,219,1377]" captionTargetId="figure-12@5.[114,1089,219,1377]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 9–14. Arabian Macrosiagon. 9 – M. elegans (Marseul, 1876), male; 10 – M. bipunctata (Fabricius, 1801), female from Dhawran; 11 – M. ferruginea (Fabricius, 1775), female from Jebel Jibir; 12 – M. oberthurii (Fairmaire, 1879), female from Bahrain; 13–14 – M. terminata (Laporte, 1840), females, two colour forms from Wadi Wurayah. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325208" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325208/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) is a 
<quantity box="[555,616,943,967]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
long male, which is completely black with light yellow, basally and apically black elytra (sexual dichroism) and fuscous antennae and tarsal segments; the elevated process at the apex of pronotum is reduced with a small cavity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,494,1287]" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,315,1038,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Biogeography.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Marseul" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[322,552,1040,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[322,552,1040,1063]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Macrosiagon elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the rather speciose 
<emphasis box="[885,907,1040,1063]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M</emphasis>
. ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[930,1035,1040,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifasciata">
<emphasis box="[930,1035,1040,1063]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">bifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ species group (
<bibRefCitation author="BATELKA J." box="[229,399,1071,1095]" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" pagination="149 - 153" refId="ref3966" refString="BATELKA J. 2008 b: Taxonomy of Palaearctic and Oriental species of the genus Macrosiagon. Part IV - addenda (Coleoptera: Ripiphoridae). Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 113: 149 - 153." type="journal article" year="2008">BATELKA 2008b</bibRefCitation>
), to which also belongs 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chobaut, 1893)" baseAuthorityName="Chobaut" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[661,957,1071,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortieri">
<emphasis box="[661,683,1072,1095]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[698,774,1072,1095]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">fortieri</emphasis>
(Chobaut, 1893)
</taxonomicName>
described from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,218,1103,1127]" name="Egypt" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Egypt</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Marseul" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[229,459,1104,1127]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[229,459,1104,1127]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Macrosiagon elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be more closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[855,997,1104,1127]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifasciata">
<emphasis box="[855,997,1104,1127]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M. bifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(an Eastern Palaearctic and Oriental species) or to 
<taxonomicName box="[563,734,1136,1159]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis box="[563,734,1136,1159]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Costa, 1859) (a Mediterranean species) than to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[290,440,1168,1191]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipunctata">
<emphasis box="[290,440,1168,1191]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">M. bipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(with which it occurs sympatrically in 
<collectingCountry box="[861,937,1167,1191]" name="Yemen" pageId="2" pageNumber="159">Yemen</collectingCountry>
) or to 
